#### Results

The final tally was "Yes-Yes." A majority decided they wanted a Scottish Parliament, and they wanted it to have the power to fiddle with taxes. Simple enough, you'd think. But then there were the nuances. Two council areas, [Dumfries and Galloway](/Dumfries_and_Galloway) and [Orkney](/Orkney), decided on a "Yes-No" split. And, curiously, more votes were cast for the first question than the second in most regions, with a rather significant number of spoilt ballots for the second question. Voter confusion, I suspect, or perhaps just apathy.

##### Question 1

The results for the first question, the one about the Parliament itself:

| Choice                                                | Votes     | %      |
| :---------------------------------------------------- | :-------- | :----- |
| I agree there should be a Scottish Parliament         | 1,775,045 | 74.29% |
| I do not agree there should be a Scottish Parliament  | 614,200   | 25.71% |
| **Valid votes**                                       | **2,389,445** | **99.50%** |
| Invalid or blank votes                                | 11,986    | 0.50%  |
| **Total votes**                                       | **2,401,431** | **100.00%** |

Registered voters/turnout: 3,973,673 / 60.43%

Broken down by council area, the "Yes" vote generally held strong, ranging from a respectable 57.3% in [Orkney](/Orkney) to a staggering 84.7% in [West Dunbartonshire](/West_Dumbartonshire).

##### Question 2

And for the tax-varying powers:

| Choice                                                                | Votes     | %      |
| :-------------------------------------------------------------------- | :-------- | :----- |
| I agree that a Scottish Parliament should have tax-varying powers     | 1,512,889 | 63.48% |
| I do not agree that a Scottish Parliament should have tax-varying powers | 870,263   | 36.52% |
| **Valid votes**                                                       | **2,383,152** | **99.21%** |
| Invalid or blank votes                                                | 19,013    | 0.79%  |
| **Total votes**                                                       | **2,402,165** | **100.00%** |

Registered voters/turnout: 3,973,673 / 60.45%

Even with the tax-varying powers, the "Yes" vote held its ground, though the margin was tighter. Most councils still favoured giving the parliament these powers, with [Dumfries & Galloway](/Dumfries_%26_Galloway) and [Orkney](/Orkney) again being the outliers, voting against.

The overall turnout by council area showed a similar pattern, with most areas hovering around the 60-65% mark, though some, like [Glasgow City](/Glasgow_City_(council_area)) and [Aberdeen City](/Aberdeen_City), dipped lower, while others like [East Dunbartonshire](/East_Dunbartonshire) and [Midlothian](/Midlothian) nudged higher.

#### Outcome

Following the "Yes-Yes" verdict, the [UK Parliament](/UK_Parliament) did what was expected and passed the [Scotland Act 1998](/Scotland_Act_1998). This act, in theory, resurrected a [Scottish Parliament](/Scottish_Parliament) for the first time since the pre-Union [Parliament of Scotland](/Parliament_of_Scotland) went dormant in 1707. The new Parliament finally took shape in May 1999, after its inaugural [election](/1999_Scottish_Parliament_election). It's worth noting that the [Conservative Party](/Conservative_Party_(UK)), despite losing their "No" campaign and all their Westminster seats in Scotland in the 1997, still had to contend with this. The Scotland Act 1998 also birthed the [Scottish Executive](/Scottish_Executive), which later morphed into what is now known as the Scottish Government.

#### Reaction to the result

Professor Tom Devine, an academic from the [University of Edinburgh](/University_of_Edinburgh), declared it "the most significant development in Scottish political history since the Union of 1707." High praise, or perhaps just stating the obvious. Then-Prime Minister [Tony Blair](/Tony_Blair) chimed in, announcing that "the era of big centralised government is over." A bold statement, considering the continued existence of the [UK Parliament](/UK_Parliament).

The leaders of the "Yes" campaign, [Donald Dewar](/Donald_Dewar) of [Scottish Labour](/Scottish_Labour) and [Alex Salmond](/Alex_Salmond) of the [Scottish National Party](/Scottish_National_Party), had their differing views on devolution versus independence. But they managed to put their disagreements aside for a brief moment of celebration. Salmond, ever the optimist, declared an independent Scotland was within his lifetime. The "No" campaign, predictably, harboured fears that this was the beginning of the end for the Union.

When [Donald Dewar](/Donald_Dewar), then [Secretary of State for Scotland](/Secretary_of_State_for_Scotland), returned to [London](/London) to enact the referendum's will, he encountered a rather uncooperative Whitehall civil service. They seemed reluctant to relinquish power and questioned the wisdom of devolving matters that had previously been handled by the Scottish Office, such as education, health, transport, police, and housing. Furthermore, details were fuzzy. The [Scottish Constitutional Convention](/Scottish_Constitutional_Convention) had neglected to clarify the role of [The Queen](/Elizabeth_II) or the finer points of tax-varying powers. A rather incomplete blueprint, if you ask me.

